Nicolas Patrick Cage III, born on March 7, 1964, in New York City, is a prominent American actor and producer, widely known for his versatile acting skills and unique persona. He comes from a rich, creative family, with his father, Nicolas Patrick Cage II, a composer, and his mother, Gretchen Schiro, an actress.

Cage's acting career took off after graduating from the University of Southern California with a degree in Theater. He made his film debut in 1986's "Basket Case," but his breakthrough came with "Raising Arizona" in 1987, in which he played the role of H. Todd Durkin. The film earned him his first Academy Award nomination for Best Supporting Actor.

Over the years, Cage has portrayed an array of diverse and memorable characters, making a mark in the film industry. Some of his most notable roles include:

- "Leaving Las Vegas" (1995), where he played a troubled alcoholic;
- "The Rock" (1996), as a U.S. Coast Guard Captain fighting against terrorists;
- "Gigli" (2003), which became a notorious box office flop;
- "National Treasure" (2004) and its sequels, where he played treasure hunter Benjamin Franklin Gates;
- "Face/Off" (1997), opposite John Travolta, for which he earned a Best Actor nomination at the BAFTA Awards;
- "Ghost Rider" (2007), a superhero action film where he played Johnny Blaze, a popular fictional character.

